AB  - The recently opened archives of Czechoslovak Security Services and the Central Committee of the Communist Party allow for a deeper examination of the state and party policies towards young people in the 1950s and 1960s. Combined with contemporary media reports and oral histories, these archival sources reveal what values and symbols youth subcultures on the eastern side of the Iron Curtain shared with their western counterparts, and what was specific and particular to eastern bloc youth subcultures. In the years preceding the Prague Spring sympathizers of rock music and western pop culture were confronting different political systems and different political circumstances. In Czechoslovakia, the leadership of the Communist Party was struggling with an economic crisis, an ideological crisis linked to the unfinished process of de-Stalinization, and an internal power struggle between conservative and liberal elements within the party. In 1966, the party launched a systematic nationwide campaign against the 'longhairs' in an attempt to establish a broad social consensus over common values. The campaign, based on conservative 'petit bourgeois' values of proper work, decent dressing, just conduct and a conservative approach towards sexual relations, succeeded in gaining public support, particularly from the older generation.
